Kemiron facility complies with EPA's Accidental Release Prevention Rule and with all applicable state codes and regulations. All of the employees handling chlorine have been thoroughly trained. This facility has a strong commitment to the safe handling of chlorine and to minimizing the probability of an accidental release.  This is achieved through a combination of personnel training, process safety equipment and operating procedures.

5. Five-year accident history. 

The Kemiron Great Lakes East Chicago facility is a new plant, and Chlorine handling is scheduled to start in May 2005. In the past 5 years there have not been any accidental releases of chlorine that led to deaths or injuries of people on- or off-site or response or restoration activities at environmental receptors in the last five years. None of the employees or contractors has been involved in any accidents related to the hazardous substances defined in section 112(r) that is stored or handled at this facility. However, Kemiron has developed and implemented an extensive program for investigating and follow-up of all accidents/incidents, which may occur in the future at the East Chicago facility.  

6. Emergency response program.

The facility has a comprehensive emergency response program.  The Emergency Response Plan contains specific actions to be taken in response to an accidental release of chlorine, procedures to inform the public and health care information.  All employees working with chlorine are given 40 hour Hazardous Waste Operator (hazwoper) training with annual 8 hour refreshers.  This plan will be coordinated with the Lake County LEPC.  

